@NODE "PROB" "Known Problems"

                            @{U}Known Problems@{UU}


@{U}Click2Front@{UU}


Some problems can occur if the Click2Front Commodity is used. We
recommend disabling it while using the editor. This is usually
best achieved by using the Exchange Commodity controller,
located in the Workbench/Tools/Commodity directory.

@{U}Lack of Memory@{UU}


If you are running low on memory then you need to reduce the number
of bitplanes being used. To do this simply click once on the
XTremeEd icon from Workbench, and select Icons->Information.
The fewer bitplanes selected the less memory is used and the 
faster the Editor will run. The maximum is 8, which is 256 colours,
and we don't recommend less than 5, or 32 colours.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "CRUN" "Crunching Files"

@{U}Crunching Files@{UU}


When you save out any tracks with the editor you will see that they
take up a large amount of room compared to our own tracks. When
you distribute them you will find that they will archive back to
being very small so they are quick to transfer and small enough
to store.

We recommend using either @{B}Lha@{UB} or @{B}Lzx@{UB}. Both may be found on various
magazine coverdiscs, as well as on PD discs and on Aminet.

If you wish to crunch/uncrunch any tracks/gfx/data permanently
then you may use @{B}CrunchMania@{UB} but we cannot include that. If files
are sent to us and are any good then we @{i}may@{ui} crunch them with
Crunchmania for you. This is only if your work is exceptional!

Crunchmania is by Thomas Schwarz who can be reached at :

Dammstrasse 12
70806 Kornwestheim
Germany

Tel: +497154/27263

Registration is $20 or DM 30 for full programs and support.


@ENDNODE


@NODE "DIST" "Distribution Rules"

@{U}Distribution Rules@{UU}


None of the materials provided by Silltunna Software may be distributed
in any form, INCLUDING graphics and track related materials. Only tracks
designed TOTALLY by the user may be legally distributed, and no profit may
be made from ANY CUSTOM TRACKS and related data without permission and 
relevant royalty payments to Silltunna Software Ltd.

If you do wish to use Silltunna Software Tracks as the basis for your own
tracks then please ensure they are sufficiently modified before releasing
them publicly. If we find tracks that have been released with very little
modified then the Author will be in big trouble! Otherwise we may turn a
blind eye if the modifications are substantial and good. Send them to
rich@xtreme.demon.co.uk (his snail address is elsewhere in this helpguide)
if you aren't certain.

When you distribute Tracks/Gfx/Sfx then please also include Installation
Instructions in the archive.  Remember that floppy users must have
all the gfx for a track contained on the same disk as the track, and that
disc must be named XTRx, where x is a number >4 .

Brief installation instructions are included in the Upgrade.Readme file.
We recommend that you keep the standard XTR directory structure in your
archives, so that e.g. Tile Gfx will all be within the Tiles directory,
and Tracks will always be in the Tracks directory, etc.

If you can crunch the files using @{" Crunchmania " link CRUN}, then please do.

When distributing graphics, remember that you will need to include Palette
files, Gradient files, and perhaps some original 256 IFF files so that
people may edit tracks using your graphics. When distributing the Tiles
you may use either the .256 or the .chk versions. The .chk versions are
generated when XTR is run and the .256 version is newer than the
.chk version, or if no .chk version exists. This allows you to edit
the Tilesets without having to tell XTR to reconvert them again. This
does, however, rely on you having in Internal Clock. If you do not have one
then you should delete existing .chk files for your Tilesets if you alter
them. The Editor can work with .chk versions as long as you include a
Palette file. We leave it to your common sense as to how much to 
include. Just remember to test the archive on a system which previously
has none of your work installed. 

All Tracks placed ANYWHERE @{B}must@{UB} also include the @{" Track.Readme " link READ} file found
on the editor disk (and XTR: directory for Hard-Drive users). This must be
filled in with the details for any tracks in the archive.
This is purely to help players & help get you the recognition you
probably(!) deserve for a track.

The Track.Readme file must also be used as the basis for the File
Description on Aminet/BBS/other.

If any new Graphics are included then the @{" Graphic.Readme " link GFXR} should also be present,
and if there are many graphics changed then those graphics should ideally be
stored in a separate archive.  If a completely new tile set is created, this
should also be stored in a seperate archive.

The Graphic.Readme file should also be used as the basis for the File
Description on Aminet/BBS/other.

The rules are similar for Sound Effects : See @{" Sfx.Readme " link SFXR}

>> Note <<

If you create a set of tracks that you would like to be placed into a
cup/season, then send the tracks (plus any associated graphics files) to:

EMail: rich@xtreme.demon.co.uk
Snail Mail: 5 Wyvern Close, Wellesbourne, WARKS, CV35 9TA

A new season file will then be created for you, and posted back.  Snail Mail
- please enclose return postage costs, if you don't, you won't be sent a new
season file.  This season file will contain the new cup/season information
for use within the game.


By using this software you agree to accept and abide by all these rules.

© Copyright Silltunna Software Ltd. 1996


@ENDNODE


